    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"387244\">Yaël Dillies</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Fourier.20transform/near/299118533\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also note that combinatorics needs the discrete Fourier transform (Fourier transform on finite groups). Not sure where that fits in the greater scheme of things.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In particular, <a href=\"https://people.maths.ox.ac.uk/greenbj/papers/addcomb2009-1.pdf\">https://people.maths.ox.ac.uk/greenbj/papers/addcomb2009-1.pdf</a> (page 5) has some comments on the most convenient normalization in the discrete setting.</p>",
